<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Original Research</div>
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>TransDigm (TDG)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of TransDigm Group — using FY2024 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated May 18, 2024 · Data: FY2024</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$9.1B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2024 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$1.88B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$31.08</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">46.5%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model to value TransDigm Group. This method attempts to figure out the value of an investment today, based on projections of how much money it will generate in the future.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>TransDigm generated <strong>$1.878 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2024. As an aerospace supplier with highly proprietary aftermarket parts, TransDigm generates cash flow margins far superior to typical industrial companies.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project FCF to grow at <strong>12% per year</strong> for the next 5 years. This assumes TransDigm will continue to execute on its core strategy: acquiring sole-source proprietary aerospace businesses, raising prices on inelastic aftermarket parts, and maintaining high operating margins.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>3.5% forever</strong>. This is slightly above typical global GDP growth, justified by long-term structural tailwinds in both commercial aerospace traffic and defense spending.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>9.5%</strong>. While TransDigm operates a highly stable business, its extremely leveraged capital structure (over $30B in debt) adds financial risk, warranting a discount rate roughly equivalent to its cost of equity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Account for extreme leverage</h4>
      <p>We add Net Cash (negative $27.5B, given the immense debt load) to Enterprise Value to arrive at Equity Value. The negative net cash is a massive drag on the final intrinsic value calculation, a common theme for private-equity-like public companies.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is highly sensitive to its core inputs. We've made three major judgment calls to project TransDigm's future cash flows.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">12%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        TransDigm has historically grown FCF at robust double-digit rates, fueled by a recovering commercial aerospace market and aggressive pricing on monopolistic aftermarket parts. 12% is a conservative estimate for continued strong execution and opportunistic bolt-on acquisitions.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">9.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        With the 10Y Treasury at 4.18%, a 9.5% discount rate represents a ~5.3% equity risk premium. Despite the stability of TDG's revenues (sole-source provider for essential flight components), the immense debt burden ($30B) demands a healthy required rate of return.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">3.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Air travel and defense spending have proven to be incredibly durable over decades. A 3.5% terminal growth rate assumes TransDigm will continue to capture a growing share of global GDP as airplanes require continuous maintenance and component replacement indefinitely.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2024)</td>
          <td>${fcf2024.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2024 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.035)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (9.5% − 3.5%))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
  <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
