                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>If you believe the market's current price is correct, the implied market expectations are roughly 16%+ FCF growth combined with an exceptionally low discount rate (warranted by their pricing power, despite the debt).</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>A strict DCF calculation can miss nuances of TransDigm's unique capital strategy.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Debt-funded dividends:</strong> TDG notoriously issues special dividends funded by debt. This returns massive cash to shareholders in ways that a traditional FCF-to-firm model struggles to fully value without adjusting for financial engineering.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive M&A:</strong> TransDigm acquires highly profitable, sole-source component businesses. If they successfully execute a few large, accretive acquisitions, FCF will scale non-linearly.</li>
    <li><strong>Inelastic pricing:</strong> Aerospace aftermarket parts are often heavily regulated and represent a tiny fraction of total airline costs, giving TDG almost unlimited pricing power.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest rate vulnerability:</strong> Over $30 billion in debt. While much is hedged or fixed, refinancing in a sustained high-rate environment could severely compress free cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory scrutiny:</strong> The Pentagon and the DoD frequently investigate TransDigm for "price gouging" on military contracts. Legislative action could force margin contraction in the defense segment.</li>
    <li><strong>Commercial cyclicality:</strong> While aftermarket parts are resilient, prolonged downturns in commercial flying (like 2020) still severely dent top-line revenue.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the DCF value so much lower than the market price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">DCF models heavily penalize extreme debt loads. Subtracting $27.5B in net debt directly destroys equity value in this model. The market, however, values TDG like a private equity fund, assuming they will roll the debt forever while continuing to expand margins. The market is pricing in continued successful M&A and highly aggressive capital allocation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why does TransDigm have so much debt?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">TransDigm operates almost like a publicly traded private equity firm. They use debt to acquire complementary businesses, optimize operations to maximize margins, and regularly issue special dividends funded by taking on more debt. They are comfortable operating with 5x-7x Net Debt to EBITDA.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How can a company have 46% operating margins?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Approximately 80% of TransDigm's revenue comes from products where they are the sole-source provider. Furthermore, their parts are critical for flight safety but represent a minuscule fraction of an airline's total operating costs. This creates massive inelasticity of demand — airlines have no choice but to pay TDG's asking price.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

